'''syslog-ng''' is a powerful, massively configurable monitoring and logging daemon.

== Installation ==

=== USE flags ===

{{USEflag|package=app-admin/syslog-ng}}

=== Emerge ===

Install {{Package|app-admin/syslog-ng}}:

{{Emerge|app-admin/syslog-ng}}

{{Note|It is a bad idea to run more than one system logger on a physical host. Other local loggers should be removed or disabled.}}

=== Additional software ===

When using a system logger such as syslog-ng, it is a wise idea to install log rotation software to appropriately trim the logs as they consume more disk space. Logrotate is a fine option:

{{Emerge|app-admin/logrotate}}

== Configuration ==

The default configuration provided by the ebuild is quite minimal. For a more comprehensive configuration see the configuration provided for [[Project:Hardened|Hardened Gentoo]] in:

{{Path|/usr/share/doc/syslog-ng-*/syslog-ng.conf.gentoo.hardened.bz2}}

=== Files ===

The default source for syslog messages is:

{{FileBox|filename=/etc/syslog-ng/syslog-ng.conf|1=
source src { unix-stream("/dev/log"); internal(); };
}}

If the system is running [[systemd]], the default source needs to be changed to the following<ref>Balabit. [https://www.balabit.com/sites/default/files/documents/syslog-ng-ose-latest-guides/en/syslog-ng-ose-guide-admin/html/configuring-sources-journal.html Collecting messages from the systemd-journal system log storage], [https://www.balabit.com/sites/default/files/documents/syslog-ng-ose-latest-guides/en/syslog-ng-ose-guide-admin/html/index.html The syslog-ng Open Source Edition 3.7 Administrator Guide], January 22nd, 2016. Retrieved on January 30th, 2016.</ref>:

{{FileBox|filename=/etc/syslog-ng/syslog-ng.conf|1=
source src { systemd-journal(); internal(); };
}}

=== Service ===

==== OpenRC ====

Add the syslog-ng daemon to the default runlevel so that logging starts on system boot:

{{RootCmd|rc-update add syslog-ng default}}

Start the syslog-ng daemon now:

{{RootCmd|rc-service syslog-ng start}}

==== systemd ====

To start the syslog-ng daemon when the system boots enable the service:

{{RootCmd|systemctl enable syslog-ng}}

To start the daemon now:

{{RootCmd|systemctl start syslog-ng}}

